segments.text: I get an education and exist and help each other exist.
That was really a strong part, Haskell, of helping each other to exist.
Give examples of that.
Where did y'all help?
Where did y'all pull together?
We pulled together in the classroom.
We pulled together in having our meals when you had a special party or something.
Boy, everybody dug as deep as they could to get together and have something.
Protected each other from upperclassmen.
It was the camaraderie and the assistance that you had from your fish old lady and from your classmates all the way through was, you couldn't do without it.
I don't know what I would have done had not I had those close, close friends that went through the same thing that I was going through.
Were there some special events that contributed to this
Were there some special Aggie traditions?
Oh, yes.
We had our parties out at the clay pits.
We had our parties out at, oh goodness, it was out here on Highway 6 and 21 intersection.
I don't know if it was VFW, not VFW, but one of those type of buildings out there.
That's where Aggie Corps units could go have their parties and drink, okay, get completely away from the campus, and that was condoned.
The clay pits was condoned.
Now, your outfit never went to the river and partied, did it?
The clay pits, of course, is on the river.
Oh, all right.
And that, and I couldn't tell you how to get the clay pits right now.
I remember one of my quack shack visits was as a result of the clay pits.
I got blistered out there and got pretty bad burns and had to get some medical attention for that.
Too much sunshine blister.
Way, way too much sunshine, you know, all day affair.
But this pulling together did silver taps and muster and...
Things like that.
Now, Haskell, of course, you know, those were very special to you.
But Silver Tap was a rarity, really.
You know, I can only recall maybe three or four Silver Taps my whole undergraduate career.
That was just not that common of an occurrence.
I mean, there were only, you know, what, 5,000 to 7,000 of us or something like that.
The community was just not that big.
So that was a little bit different than maybe what it is today.
It might also have been a little bit more hollowed back then, too, because when they cut lights out, they cut lights out.
And there was no talking.
I mean, it was quiet as a mouse on that campus and was until the next morning.
I recall that we went back to our dorm and went to bed after super tabs.
And nobody fudged, nobody cheated?
No.
No, no, it was very solemn.
That's what I heard.
Very solemn.
What did you and your buddies, how often did y'all see and what did y'all think about the president of Texas A&M in that era?
That man who was the new president when you got here.
You know, very visible.
He was visible on campus.
His dog was visible on campus.
Now, was his dog treated equally with Reveille?
Oh, I hope to tell you, more equally.
Absolutely.
You bet he was.
Ranger had the run of the campus every bit as much as Reveille did.
You know, I don't have any strong recollections as an undergraduate student too much of him, other than he was visible, he was available.
I believe that, I'm trying to think when his home burned.
That's after, that's 68.
Was that 68?
See, I was a PhD student at that time.
Actually, I was teaching and working full-time, but I was going to school part-time to try to finish up a doctorate degree.
But I remember my father-in-law helping move things out of that house as it was burning.
My father-in-law worked for the ground maintenance department at the university.
Let's see.
This is another note to the typist.
Please put this in as an editorial note.
According to Edwin Cooper, Edwin H. Cooper, who was Mr.

Rudder's assistant at that time, as the fire in the house gradually, over a period of the morning, got worse, they were moving things out, and Ed said, as far as he knows, the last thing that they got out of the house, before they couldn't go back in at all and get anything,
Mr. Rutter pulled him aside and told him to go in through the back door into a certain closet and look up on the second
there was a case of Tiger Teague's favorite whiskey, and to get that and bring that out, that he didn't want that to be discovered by anybody else.
My father-in-law says he brought it out.
Is that right?
Okay.
I don't know.
He told me that many times, that one of the last things that came out of that house was a case of whiskey.
What did you all think about President Runner?
What was your attitude about him?
How did you all feel about him?
Haskell, I think my knowledge and awareness and attitudes of Rudder were so...

maybe rethought and recolored in later years that I don't really remember too much of those undergraduate academic years because I had the opportunity to, you know, to sit around Rudder a few times later on in my career.
And so I have a different perspective maybe.
Do you agree with me in looking back in retrospect, he did not make a lot of speeches.
No.
He was not colorful.
But there was no doubt that he was in charge.
He was in charge, and he had people that was in charge.
I remember the director of campus security as an undergraduate student.
He was an old Texas Ranger.
Oh, gosh, Haskell.
I can't remember that name either.
But he, too, was in charge.
Yes, and when he said that something was going to happen on campus, it happened that way.
And you know where that was coming from, not only that he was an old ranger, a Texas ranger, but it was coming from Earl Rudder, okay?
Now, Dean Hannigan was not here.
Yes.
Was he?
Yes.
All right.
What did you all think of him?
All the rumors were that Dean Hannigan was a very stern disciplinarian that
tolerated absolutely no nonsense, and he had a cadre of folks working for him.
I wish I could think of some of those guys' names that were just as tough as he were.
They were, listen, when you put the Commandant and Dean Hannigan
And those folks that worked for Dean Hannigan together, they were a bunch of stern disciplinarians that did not want a lot of nonsense going on.
And they tolerated you going out and getting into some devilishness every once in a while.
But they were pretty, they were stern disciplinarians.
Every last one of them.
I remember that.
Now, in the fall of 1963, you're a serious student.
Very serious.
You're married.
Very married.
And where were you when you heard the news just before Thanksgiving?
Kennedy, Haskell, I was sitting in an old Studebaker, and by this time it was a 59 large station wagon Studebaker.
And I don't remember all the particulars of it, but I remember getting out and walking into the A&M Press, now the A&M Printing Center, where my wife was working.
And I can't put all of those events together, but I remember it was just a lot of goodness what has happened.
So you heard it on the car radio?
Yes, I did.
In my case, I had just finished class in Nagel Hall when in Garland Bayless's office, we were going to go to lunch at 1 o'clock to beat the crowd to go to the MSC.
And I said, come on, let's go, let's go.
He said, I'm listening to the radio.
And I said, you can listen to it.
He said, listen.
And at that moment, I leaned over and Walter Cronkite said, I've just been handed a bulletin.
President Kennedy is dead.
I want to believe that I had probably gone to the printing center or the A&M Press to pick up
Etta to have lunch together, or maybe even to have sack lunch there in the building.
I do not remember the real particular, I don't even remember us leaving there and going to lunch as a matter of fact, but that's where I was when that happened.
Were you aware during that time, and if you were, are you able to comment about any secret fraternities at Texas A&M?
Not aware of any?
No, I was not.
But no, I knew of none.
All right, back to, I can't think of any other events during your undergraduate days that would have caused you to remember where you were when you heard the news that.
No.
Because I can't think of any.
Like December 7, 41, everybody remembers that one.
Yeah, I was three months old.
Let's see.
I do remember my undergraduate years.
I remember A&M Integrated.
Oh, yes, describe.
First of all.
Describe.
First of all.
It happened.
What was the attitude of the typical students that you knew
What were the attitude about the students about a non-compulsory core?
You know, that probably was, it was just kind of, I don't think there was any big hassle one way or the other for anybody.
I don't see that as having been just a real blazing issue.
Co-education?
Probably a little bit more of an issue, talked about a little bit more often.
Maybe don't need them, why, that sort of thing.
If there had been a referendum, what do you think the vote would have been?

I may be wrong, but I think it may have been let them in, because I can remember, and so many of us can remember, writing your post office box up at TWU or at Sam Houston and picking the girls up off the buses when they came into town.
See, I believe if there had been a secret ballot...
I think they would have voted the way I would have voted, let the women in.
Yeah, I believe that.
What about integration?
It just happened.
There was no fanfare to it.
Was there any opposition at all?
No.
I don't even remember anyone even saying that, hey, it's going to happen or anything else.
It just happened.
And best I recall, I think it was when I was a senior.
I think it was fall of 63 when it happened, and it just happened.
No, there was no opposition and very, very smooth.
And as far as I know, Sterling Evans was one of the key men in making it happen when it did.
Let's see, you didn't do any Aggie hitchhiking, so you don't have any hitchhiking.
No, I didn't have to.
My brother did.
He tells a lot of stories about it, but I did not.
Did you ever get any Tessie dates?
Oh, goodness, yes.
Now, how did you meet some Tessies in the first place?
How did you know who to write to?
just wrote a post office box number.
And if it came back, there was no such post office box number, you'd come up with a post office box number, you know?
Did you have some fun occasions?
Yeah, there were good times.
Now, haven't I heard about beast buckets and moose pots?
Moose pots, yes.
Those were true, those were true.
And that was for the...
the guy that had the ugliest date.
And they probably had something on the other end as well.
Oh, yeah, that's true.
Yeah, those happened.
They sure did.
When the girls came down here, how were they treated?
Oh, with a great deal of respect.
I mean, it was just like, hey, I mean, you know, it's not like they came down here for wild parties.
They came down here to enjoy a weekend, football games and what have you.
No, it was very sane, very docile, very nice.
Now, you were not a dancer, so you didn't take any of them to dances.
Oh, I tried to.
Oh, did you?
No, I was not that successful at it.
But, yeah, we went, sure, yeah.
And we made all the military balls and that sort of thing and, you know, stumbled around and that sort of thing.
Student indulgences then, what were Aggies drinking, those who did drink?
Haskell, you know, you could go out to the river.
Whiskey Bridge.
Whiskey Bridge and buy, oh, the,
They'd buy gin, slow gin, you know, wine.
I can remember the old saying, you know, what's the word?
Thunderbird.
What's the price?
30 thrice.
What's the reason?
It's drinking season.
What's the reaction?
Satisfaction.
They'd make us as freshmen go through that over and over and over.
And as far as I can recall, there was only a couple places where you could find beer.
There was just not that many places.
Uncle Ed's was still going?
Yes, Uncle Ed's was still going.
Goodness, that seems like that's about it.
Most of the drink in high school was restricted really to the core outfit parties that would happen once or twice a year.
And that was about it.
And there was an arrangement to get everybody back to the campus.
Oh, yes.
Yes, there was, as a matter of fact.
In fact, do you remember, in all of your undergraduate days, do you remember a death, DWI death?
No.
No, I do not.
I do remember seeing drunk Aggies, especially after court parties, but I don't remember ever hearing or knowing of a drunk DIW deaf, no.
And occasionally an Aggie would hide a fifth or a pint somewhere in the wall?
Yes, and occasionally get caught.
There wasn't a bootlegger, and I've never heard of a bootlegger in Brazos County.
Did you ever hear of any bootlegger?
I would know of guys that would go somewhere and come back into town with contraband liquor.
And Pedlet.
Oh, and Pedlet.
Yeah, sure.
But there was no dealer, no bootlegger dealer in Browns County that I've ever heard of.
No.
No, nothing I know of, no.
Was the chicken ranch still in existence?
Yes, the chicken ranch was in existence.
And was there a kind of an Aggie tradition supposedly to?
Haskell, I think maybe there was some tradition there, but I don't think it was near as great as what everybody made it out to be.
As the story has become?
As the story has become.
I can remember once or twice in the Corps,
the whistle jock.
And I'm pretty sure some upperclassmen put the whistle jock up to this, but blowing the whistle and hollering, fall out for the chicken wrench.
And, you know, everybody look out in the hall, there'll be nobody, you know, really going anywhere, but I can remember that happening.
And
But I don't remember, I don't know of anybody that really, that was a place that Aggies went to.
Oh, it was talked about, and I'm sure it did.
I'm sure there were frequent visits from A&M students to the chicken ranch.
There was all sorts of stories back there.
You go there because that's where all the University of Texas girls were.
So I don't know how much validity to any of those old stories were.
But yeah, it was still there.
In terms of smoking, what were Aggies smoking?
Oh, cigarettes, man.
They were smoking Kimmel's, Sir Walter Raleigh's.
Some guys were smoking Kuhl's.
They were menthol, menthol Kuhl's.
That was pretty much it.
Some of us would, I even smoked a pipe a little bit during those days, you know.
Not much cigar.
No.
Chewing tobacco?
No.
Didn't see much chewing.
I don't recall anyone chewing tobacco, as a matter of fact.
Now, I chewed tobacco when I worked for the highway department during summers and what have you.
I'd get out on a dirt job, and I'd chew tobacco.
I claimed to keep dirt out of my mouth.
But I don't remember chewing being a frequent thing on campus.
Smoking was pretty heavy.
They gave cigarettes away on campus.
We got the little four cigarette packs.
Particulate registration.
Yeah, you got it.
Uh-huh.
Did you even know the terminology of drugs?
I'm glad you asked that.
Let me tell you a story.
When I was in high school, even though some people call that some of the redneck part of Texas and the architects area, there was no drinking problem or a drug problem.
In fact, I can remember four of my high school classmates drinking beer, getting caught,

and the school principal calling a school assembly in the auditorium on a Monday after these guys were caught on a Saturday drinking beer and making all four of them stand on the stage and apologize to the student body.
And that kind of put a quietus on that kind of nonsense.
I honestly do not remember even hearing the word marijuana when I was in high school.
And no, there was no drug culture that I am aware of, not even in the slightest, when I was at A&M.
It was a simpler era.
It definitely was.
All right, you say that racial integration went very smoothly.
Were you on campus when some of the first women enrolled?
Yeah, see, I was, well, let me see now.
See, there was a time period in there where they were doing some summer classes.
Oh, they always could do that.
And they were doing, let me think here a minute.
Maybe there was some preliminary letting the ladies enroll or make application for vet school or something.
I can't remember what that was.
But of course I was teaching when we opened the doors.
I can remember my first engineering class I taught where I had a few ladies in the classroom.
Yeah, I can remember that well.
What was it like for them?

Oh, I'm sure it was strained in a lot of ways for them that they were looking around, but I think most of them knew, especially in engineering, hey, we're going into a male-dominated world anyway, so this is just the way it's going to be, and maybe even until today engineering is still a little bit male-dominated, but...
I think that was a very smooth assimilation as well.
I don't recall it being any particular harassment.
I'm aware of some of the minor, I call them minor, some of the things that happened, you know, with the girls in the corps and band and some of those things.
But as far as having girls in my classroom and what have you, well, that was just as smooth as it could be.
I remember later on when I was in the dean's office,
having to instruct a few faculty members to tone their classes down a little bit.
Had to threaten to remove one from the classroom because of his obnoxious
vocabulary that he just couldn't seem to clean up for his classes.
He should have been cleaned up for the males, as far as that goes, but it was particularly obnoxious to the ladies, and I can remember that.
The early, the first women, female students, academically, were they, in general, quite capable?
Haskell, you know, the ones that I had in the civil engineering classes, I don't remember any of them being poor students.
I don't remember a single one being a poor student.
I think that's been true.
And when I went to the dean's office, you know, I hit the dean's office part-time in 74.
and then replaced Cliff Ransdell, if you will, in 75.
I say replaced.
Cliff Ransdell was ready to retire.
In fact, Cliff stayed with me for a year on a part-time basis to make sure I didn't fumble and fall too many times.
And I remember those days, our girls were just absolutely exceptional.
And we had more of them in the harder curriculum.
We had them in chemical engineering.
some of those areas, and they were just absolutely tearing the curves up.
They were just outstanding students and taking a lot of leadership positions in the Student Engineers Council and those type of organizations.
So, no, this was a very smooth assimilation into the College of Engineering, I can assure you, and we were delighted to have them, absolutely delighted to have them.
If you'll remember, the 70 to 80 was that real dynamic growth period, and especially if you take the 74, 75 through 80 period, that's when A&M just blew.
And when I walked out the doors my last day as a dean in the College of Engineering, there was 9,070 engineering students, and it was a handful.
I mean, it was, and most of those were undergraduate, you know.
That was what year?
That was 1980.
So that engineering within 15, 16 years had 2,000 more students than the institution had had.
You got it.
Absolutely.
It sure did.
Yes.
Yeah, that was such a dynamic period, but it was fun.
That was the most fun part of perhaps my career was those years over there.
Back to undergraduate days, when you bought that ring, do you remember how much it cost?
Where did you get that money?
My brother.
My brother came through with that $28.
And, you know, the story is the Association of Farmer Students was paying the other half of the value of the ring.
How did you feel when you put it on?
There is no way to describe it.
You know, you just couldn't hold your hand out far enough.
You couldn't show it off enough.
It was just absolutely an unbelievable event in life.
Why are Aggies so, why is an Aggie ring so important to Aggies?
It's a symbol.
I mean, it's a designation that you belong, man, that you're part of it.
And there's no question that you're a part of it, that you didn't quit too early, that you didn't make it.
You really are a part of what A&M is all about, and that tells everyone that sees you, man, I'm a part of something great.
And I still believe that.
Oh, I do too.
Until today, I believe that.
And as an outside observer, I think one of the keys is that it hasn't changed in design, appearance, and so forth.
but just a tiny, tiny bit.
That's right.
So that if you ever recognized it one place, it will look the same.
That's right.
And you've heard the stories of being stopped everywhere imaginable.
Haskell, that ring has been seen all over these states for sure.
What are your favorite ring stories, where somebody saw it or...
Oh, my wife and I and the three kids made a summer trip to D.C.
I had a summer presentation to the Highway Research Board of the National Academy of Sciences up there one summer.
And we were standing on a corner in the... Oh, goodness.
The...
What do you call the area in between the Capitol and the... Oh, my.
My brain gone to sleep.
Boy, mine went to sleep on me, not the quadrangle, but in the mall area.
And there was a high-ranking military officer.
I don't remember now exactly whether he was Army or Air Force.
It really doesn't matter, but he saw my Aggie ring, introduced himself, and he was an Aggie and said, what are you doing here?
I said, well, I've got a presentation later today.
I told him where it was, and I said, my wife and the three kids are going to do a little tour around Michigan
the mall area here and maybe catch some of the Smithsonian exhibits and what have you.
And it was almost lunchtime and he said, well, what are the plans for lunch today?
And I said, well, I'm going to be leaving here in just a few minutes and I've told them to find something.
He said, well, they just found it.
And he carried my wife and the three kids to lunch.
So I remember that one very well.
And other occasions, airports.
Always.

You know, I've traveled most of my professional career, hundreds of air flights, and very seldom would you ever go into an airport, even strange airports, that someone would say, hey, what class are you?
Or come over and introduce themselves.
You've never lost it.
I've never lost mine.
My brother lost his three years ago, class 51.
It was completely slick.
He lost his, and he's wearing one now that looks like a brand new one.
He was almost self-conscious about it, but no, I never lost mine.
My daughter lost her first one in Lake Somerville, and I lost it three or four years after graduation.
That's it.
And you didn't buy senior boots?
Oh, yes.
Oh, you did?
Yes, I did.
Where'd you get them?
I had two pair of senior boots.
I had a pair of senior boots that my sister gave me from a friend that she knew in Houston, and they were my everyday boots, okay, that first semester of my senior year when I was in the Corps.
And then I bought a pair of hand-me-down boots from an upperclassman that fit, and those were my drill and ceremonies senior boots.
So I had two pair, and I sold the drill and ceremony, the real nice pair, and I kept the old pair.
I still have those.
And was your first final review wearing boots a special time?
Yes, it was very special.
I can recall it like it was yesterday.
Had special people in town for the occasion, and yeah, it was very special.
And commencement, when you graduated?
My mom came down, and all of my brothers and sisters came down, all five of them.
My wife and her family was there, and I think even her sister and her husband, and he was an Aggie, I think they were there.
Very special occasion, yes, very special.
Every name called?
Oh, yes, every name called.
I don't remember it being Roger Feldman, but every name was called, and that was a very special feeling to walk across that stage.
As you look back on those undergraduate days, how well did it prepare you for A&M's undergraduate program prepare you for your future?
Haskell, there was no question when I graduated I thought I could slay the world.
I really believed that, that I was as well prepared as anyone anywhere to do whatever I well pleased to do, whether it was in engineering or do something else.
And I had committed to myself during that senior year that I was going into academics.
And my department head, who was Saul Wright, he was civil engineering department head when I left,
Told me I could go to graduate school, but I need to go out and have an adjustment for a couple of years.
